article.description: Fresno State clinched its second consecutive trip to the NCAA tournament.
article.headline: Fresno State clinches second straight trip to NCAA tourney
article.linkText: Fresno State staves off Nevada for WAC crown
article.story:
RENO, Nev. -- Fresno State used stingy defense to earn a second straight trip to the NCAA tournament.

Jaleesa Ross scored 22 points to help the top-seeded Bulldogs beat Nevada 56-49 on Saturday in the championship game of the Western Athletic Conference tournament.

Joh-Teena Filipe added 12 points and 14 rebounds for the top-seeded Bulldogs (24-8), who shot only 31 percent from the field but outrebounded the Wolf Pack 51-34. They also held Nevada's three-time all-WAC guard Dellena Criner to only nine points after she averaged 23 in the two previous WAC tourney games.

Fresno State coach Adrian Wiggins said a lot of the credit for shutting down Criner went to Ross, a 5-foot-8 sophomore from Pinole, Calif., who became the first women's player in the WAC to be named the most valuable player on the all-tournament team two years in a row.

"It started with Jaleesa Ross," Wiggins said. "She did really well, but she had a lot of help, too. Our post players really ran the floor hard and turned around and we would double Criner if she did get past Jaleesa. We tried to make her give the ball up."

Fresno State, which shared the regular season title with Louisiana Tech, tied the school's previous best record set in 2005-06.

Filipe said she zeroed in on the rebounding while watching videotape of Nevada's 91-88 overtime victory over Louisiana Tech in the semifinals Friday night.

"I was just thinking if we don't rebound, we're not going to win the game," she said. "They have good post players and they're active."

Nevada coach Jane Albright said it was the key to the game.

"It's really hard to beat a team when you give up 26 offensive rebounds," she said. "We got beat at our own game, which is rebounding. They were getting two, three and four looks at it every time."

Shavon Moore had a team-high 10 points and eight rebounds for the third-seeded Wolf Pack (18-14), who appeared in their first WAC title game ever and were bidding for their first trip to the NCAA tourney.

Down 31-20 at the half, Nevada fought back to tie the game at 47 before Ross scored inside and was fouled with 3 minutes to play. She missed the free throw, but then nailed a 3-pointer with 2:06 left to give the Bulldogs a 52-47 lead.

Moore scored off a rebound to make it 52-49 but LaShay Fears scored inside to put Fresno State up 54-49 at 1:11.

Filipe missed the front end of a one-and-one to keep Nevada's hopes alive but Marnique Arnold blocked Megan Cherry's shot from the top of the key and Ross followed with a pair of free throws with 31 seconds left to seal the win.

Fresno State missed 11 of its first 14 shots before Ross hit consecutive 3-pointers, Filipe added a third and Ross another during a 12-0 run that put the Bulldogs on top 20-14 8:45 before the half.

Trailing 31-20 at the half, Nevada opened with a 13-3 run that included a pair of 3-pointers by Johnna Ward and five points from Criner to cut the lead to 34-33. They went ahead 37-36 when Moore followed a 17-footer with a pair of free throws with 14 minutes remaining and held their last lead 41-40 midway through the half when Cherry followed a layup with a pair of free throws.

Filipe scored inside to start a 7-0 run for the Bulldogs and went ahead 47-41 on Ross's layup with 6:37 left.

Nevada freshman Kayla Williams scored, Criner turned a steal into a layup then Moore stole the ball and fed Brandi Jones for another layup for the 47-all tie before the Bulldogs pulled away.
